description.plain:
Backed by production from rapper-producer JPEGMAFIA, Curry details the prevalence of police brutality, gun culture and violence, specifically in the US.

In an March 2022, interview with Loud and Quiet, Denzel stated, he feels carrying a weapon is necessary to “protect myself from the people that are supposed to protect me.” On February 27, 2014, Curry’s brother, Treon “Lotto Tree” Johnson was tased to death by police.

JPEGMAFIA has collaborated with Curry on multiple occasions, both as a producer and feature artist, previously on Peggy’s EP! track, “BALD REMIX”, as well as Curry’s TA13OO track, “VENGEANCE”.

The beat for this track had been originally intended for Danny Brown as can be seen in this clip from a Twitch stream.

annotations:
I’ma give them what they gave us on the first grade
 No remorse, I’ma give them boys pain, we sing, sing
Walkin

I’ma give them what they gave us on the first grade
 No remorse, I’ma give them boys pain, we sing, sing

Denzel is referring to the (possibly racially charged) bullying he received as a kid in the first line. He feels as if his gun will now allow him to do this, and threatens to use it later, proclaiming

him or me, I guess I pop him
Way before he shoot, I shot ‘em, plottin’ from the get then got ‘em
They ain’t fuck with niggas since the greatest of the grandfathers bought ’em
Talking about white people’s view on black people.

Him or me, I guess I pop him
 Way before he shoot, I shot ‘em, plottin’ from the get then got ’em

These lines have two interpolations:                                                             Denzel is speaking as a paranoid white person, scared of a black man. This leads him to decide to not hesitate and shoot him before the black man gets the chance to fire on him.
 Denzel is speaking from his own perspective, scared that a white man will shoot him before he has a chance to respond.
 Both indicate the same meaning however: Paranoia and gun control.
911, emergency will murder me the day I call ’em

As a black man, Zel feels that the institution that is there to protect him would murder him if he calls them. This line comes in wake of the early 2020s police brutality murder of black people, such as George Floyd, Nathaniel Pickett II, and Breonna Taylor.
This line also stems from the fact that on February 27, 2014, Curry’s brother, Treon “Lotto” Johnson, was tased to death by police.
My little weapon gave me power when I aimed it

Call back to Nas' track “I Gave You Power”, however, that story is being told from the point of view of the gun.

It is also a reference to the Lupe Fiasco song “Little Weapon”

So much pain I’ve endured, now I’m painless
 I got the juice, my only friend is my stainless

Grewing up in Carol City, Denzel is aware of the difficult social situation that the African-American community has to face regularly, as he states:

It didn’t hit me that I was living in the hood until I became a teenager. My cousin got shot in the chest eight times right down the street. It just kept happening, all these murders. Going round Carol City, seeing all these RIP buttons, you realise: I don’t live in the suburbs.

– Denzel Curry, inews UK

He is not just dealing with violence and crime, but is also confronting the police brutality that has scarred his life:

My brother was killed by police and I’ve got to live with that every day. So when it comes down to talking about police brutality, I do it every chance I get, because that’s happened in my family. It happened to Trayvon Martin. That could have been any one of us.

– Denzel Curry, inews UK
All I need is me, myself and I and also my revolver

Denzel interpolates the chorus and title from Long Island, New York trio De La Soul’s August 1989 rap hit “Me Myself and I”:

It’s just me myself and I
It’s just me myself and I
It’s just me myself and I

This is the second time on the album, with the first being on the album’s lead single Walkin. On this track, Denzel says “and my revolver” compared on Walkin where he says “Got in touch with my soul.”

On Walkin, Denzel discusses his struggles in walking through life, while here he needs the gun to make it in life.
Crackers out here shootin’ joggers, trouble makin’ firestarters
“Cracker” is a racial epithet directed towards white people. Denzel alludes to the 2020 murder of Ahmaud Arbery, who was shot and killed by two white men while he was jogging.
The world is darker than the integration of a Brooklyn Dodger
Zel is referencing the integration of Jackie Robinson into the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1947

description.plain:
“CoolHand” is the lead single off of Buzzy Lee’s EP Facepaint. The song covers the topic of trying to carry a cool facade on social media, and the anxiety and stress that it can cause on someone’s wellbeing.
Buzzy less said in an interview with Atwood Magazine:

I wanted to write a song about how our self-worth is so wrapped up in the ways we present ourselves on social media. There’s this constant hunger for validation, and it takes a toll — it’s all nonsense but we do it anyway.”
